## 1. Business Understanding

### 1.1 Problem Statement
YouTube content creators and brands need to understand audience sentiment to improve content strategy and engagement. Manual analysis of thousands of comments is impractical. This project aims to build an automated sentiment classification system for YouTube comments.

### 1.2 Objectives
- Develop a machine learning model to classify YouTube comments into positive, negative, and neutral sentiment
- Compare traditional ML approaches (TF-IDF + Logistic Regression) with deep learning models (LSTM, BERT)
- Achieve F1-score > 0.80 on test set
- Handle unique challenges of YouTube comments (emojis, slang, spam)

### 1.3 Success Criteria
- **Primary:** F1-score ≥ 0.80 on balanced test set
- **Secondary:** Advanced model outperforms baseline by ≥ 10% F1-score
- **Tertiary:** Model generalizes across different video categories

### 1.4 Business Value
- Content creators can identify negative feedback quickly
- Brands can monitor sentiment for marketing campaigns
- Platform moderation can prioritize toxic comments
- Researchers can analyze public opinion at scale

