## 2. Research Question & Hypothesis

### 2.1 Research Question
**"Can transformer-based models (BERT/DistilBERT) significantly outperform traditional machine learning approaches for sentiment classification of YouTube comments?"**

### 2.2 Hypothesis (Testable, Falsifiable, Reproducible)

**H1 (Primary):** A fine-tuned DistilBERT model will achieve F1-score > 0.80 on classifying YouTube comments into positive/negative/neutral sentiment.

**H2 (Comparative):** DistilBERT will outperform a TF-IDF + Logistic Regression baseline by at least 10% in F1-score.

**H3 (Feature Engineering):** Including emoji features and comment metadata (likes, word count) will improve model performance by at least 3% compared to text-only models.

**Null Hypothesis:** There is no significant difference (p > 0.05) between transformer models and traditional ML approaches for this task.

### 2.3 Why This is Testable
- Clear metrics: F1-score, accuracy, precision, recall
- Defined threshold: 0.80 F1-score
- Comparative baseline: TF-IDF + Logistic Regression
- Statistical testing: McNemar's test for model comparison

### 2.4 Why This is Falsifiable
- If DistilBERT achieves F1 < 0.80, H1 is rejected
- If improvement over baseline < 10%, H2 is rejected
- Results can prove hypotheses wrong

### 2.5 Why This is Reproducible
- Public dataset from Kaggle
- Fixed train/test split (80/20, random_state=42)
- All code in GitHub with requirements.txt
- Documented preprocessing steps
- Model hyperparameters specified

